<div class='bookAuthorProfile__about'>

<span id="freeTextContainer2404304201879473915">Thomas Hammerken (or Hammerlein -- both mean &quot;little hammer&quot;) / Thomas de Kempis / Thomas Hamerken von Kempen was born at Kempen (hence the &quot;A Kempis&quot;) in the duchy of Cleves in Germany around 1380. He was educated by a religious order called the Brethren of the Common Life, and in due course joined the order, was ordained a priest, became sub-prior of his house (in the low Countries), and died 25</span>
  <span id="freeText2404304201879473915" style="display:none">Thomas Hammerken (or Hammerlein -- both mean "little hammer") / Thomas de Kempis / Thomas Hamerken von Kempen was born at Kempen (hence the "A Kempis") in the duchy of Cleves in Germany around 1380. He was educated by a religious order called the Brethren of the Common Life, and in due course joined the order, was ordained a priest, became sub-prior of his house (in the low Countries), and died 25 July 1471 (his feast is observed a day early to avoid conflict with that of James bar-Zebedee the Apostle).<br /><br />Thomas is known almost entirely for composing or compiling a manual of spiritual advice known as <i>The Imitation of Christ</i>, in which he urges the reader to seek to follow the example of Jesus Christ and to be conformed in all things to His will.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2404304201879473915" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

